<hl>
<seg id=1> Thailand appreciated Nguon Soeur's honesty. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Reported from Bangkok by Liu Zhenting. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The Thailand government welcomed that Nguon Soeur and Nong Xie, two important members of Khmer Rouge, showed their honesty to Phnom Penh yesterday. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Spokesman of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs Gusa said:" Nguon and Nong's honesty will be important for Cambodian national conciliation." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Gusa reiterated that Thailand would never support any part of Cambodia to do any activities of subversion. </seg>
<seg id=6> Once Thailand found that any foreign military forces used the territory of Thailand to carry out some action, Thailand would stop them and bring them to justice. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> He also said that in May, Thailand signed the Agreement of Extraditing Criminals with the Hun Sen government. Therefore, Thailand could hand over the Cambodian criminals to the Phnom Penh government. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> According to the news from Phnom Penh, Thai Foreign Minister Surin had invited Cambodian Foreign Minister Ung Huot to visit Bangkok early next year, discussing the bilateral territory security and the thousands of Cambodian refugees who were still in Thailand, and considering resuming the training of personnel for Cambodia. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> In the middle of this month the Summit Conference of ASEAN in Hanoi decided to accept Cambodia as the tenth member country and the minister of ASEAN had prepared a formal ceremony in Hanoi to welcome Cambodia. </seg>
</p>
